Other Answers are correct. 

## Code point 

Let me add that this code uses the outmoded type `char` which has been essentially broken since Java 2, and legacy since Java 5. As a 16-bit value, `char` is physically incapable of representing most characters. 

Instead, use [code point][1] integer numbers. 

As an alternative to [concatenating][2] via the `+` (PLUS SIGN) operator, you may choose to call [`String#concat`][3]. Same effect, choose according to your tastes. 

```java
String org = &quot;Welcome&quot;;
String rev = &quot;&quot;;

int[] codePoints = org.codePoints().toArray() ;
for ( int index = codePoints.length()-1 ; index &gt;= 0 ; index -- ) {
    int codePoint = codePoints[ index ]
    String s = Character.toString( codePoint );
    rev = rev.concat( s );  // ⬅️  String#concat does the same job as + (PLUS SIGN) operator… concatenates strings.

}
System.out.println(rev);
```

## `StringBuilder`

Even better would be use of a class deigned for building up longer strings: [`StringBuilder`][4]. 

Use of that class *may* be more efficient in some versions of Java. More importantly, it expresses your intention to accumulate characters into a longer string. 

```java
String org = &quot;Welcome&quot;;
String rev;

int[] codePoints = org.codePoints().toArray() ;
StringBuilder builder = new StringBuilder() ;
for ( int index = codePoints.length()-1 ; index &gt;= 0 ; index -- ) {
    int codePoint = codePoints[ index ]
    sb.appendCodePoint( codePoint ) ;

}
rev = sb.toString() ;
System.out.println(rev);
```

## `SequencedCollection#reversed` 

[Java 21][5]+ gained the new feature of [sequenced collections][6]. `List` now offers a [`reversed`][7] method which produces a view onto the original list but with an encounter order that goes in reverse. As a view onto the original, this method works even on an [unmodifiable list][8]. 

If we make a [`List`][9] from our stream of code points, we can call `reversed` instead of the complicated `for` loop seen above. 

A `List` must contain objects rather than primitive values. So we call [`IntStream#boxed`][10] to wrap each `int` code point as a [`Integer`][11] object. 

We collect those code points in reverse by using a `StringBuilder`, similar to section above.

The resulting code is a one-liner:

```java
String rev =
        &quot;Welcome&quot;
                .codePoints ( )
                .boxed ( )
                .toList ( )
                .reversed ( )
                .stream ( )
                .collect ( StringBuilder :: new , StringBuilder :: appendCodePoint , StringBuilder :: append )
                .toString ( );
```


  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_point
  [2]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concatenation
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html#concat(java.lang.String)
  [4]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api//java.base/java/lang/StringBuilder.html
  [5]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_version_history#Java_21
  [6]: https://openjdk.org/jeps/431
  [7]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/List.html#reversed()
  [8]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/List.html#unmodifiable
  [9]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/List.html
  [10]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/stream/IntStream.html#boxed()
  [11]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Integer.html

