Well, I think your first approach has `n+1` [issue](https://vladmihalcea.com/n-plus-1-query-problem/) because you&#39;re querying `getOne` or `findById` inside loop. If you turn on `spring.jpa.show-sql=true` and count the number of queries, it&#39;s going to be `pageSize + 1` (and another 1 for `counting page`). This is the root cause of the problem.

There are several ways to solve it, but the simplest I can see in your post is, instead of using methods `getOne` or `findById` create this method in `Repository`
```
List&lt;ListingEntity&gt; findByIdIn(Collection&lt;Long&gt; ids);
``` 
Then apply it to service
```
@Transactional(readOnly = true)
public Page&lt;Listing&gt; search(ListingSearchParameters params) {
  Page&lt;Long&gt; pageOfListingIds = listingSearchRepo.searchForListingIds(params);
  List&lt;ListingEntity&gt; listingEntities = repo.findByIdIn(pageOfListingIds.getContent());
  List&lt;Listing&gt; listings = convertToScoredListings(listingEntities);
  return new PageImpl&lt;&gt;(listings, pageable, pageOfListingIds.getTotalElements());
}

@Transactional
public Listing convertToScoredListings(List&lt;ListingEntity&gt; listingEntities) {
  return listingEntities.stream()
    .map(entity -&gt; {
       var score = scoringFunc.score(eachListing);
       return ModelMappings.toListing(eachListing, score);
    })
    .collect(toList());
}
```
Now you can check it, there&#39;re only 3 queries generated by Hibernate (select ids, select count, select listingEntities by ids)

The second part of post is interesting, multi-threads to improve performance. Yeah could be, but it&#39;s going to be helpful when we apply for writing data instead of reading like this (only 3 queries).

I ended up solving this by using a `TransactionTemplate` in my `ExecutorService` to create sessions whenever a thread was run asynchronously. The basic strategy was to create my own `ExecutorService` subclass that simply wrapped the submitted tasks in a transaction:

```
public class TransactionalExecutorService implements ExecutorService {
  private final ExecutorService internalExecutor;
  private final TransactionTemplate txnTemplate;

  public TransactionalExecutorService(
      int threadCount,
      PlatformTransactionManager transactionManager
  ) {
    internalExecutor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(threadCount);
    txnTemplate = new TransactionTemplate(transactionManager);
  }

  private Runnable wrapInTransaction(Runnable threadWork) {
    return () -&gt; txnTemplate.execute((txnStatus) -&gt; {
      threadWork.run();
      return null;
    });
  }

  @Override
  public void execute(Runnable command) {
    internalExecutor.execute(wrapInTransaction(command));
  }

  /* ...similar implementations for submit/invoke methods */
}
```

It works, but it still feels like I&#39;m missing something that the framework would already provide, or misunderstanding a concept.

