As Jorn said, you are far better off setting the classpath at runtime.  If at all possible, you should do it that way.

But your question seems to indicate that you can’t, so…

The first problem is that URLs have a limited set of characters they are allowed to contain.  A URL is *not* allowed to contain a backslash character.

Therefore, this line is incorrect:

    URL jarURL = new URL(&quot;file:&quot; + &quot;C:\\Users\\Test\\Downloads\\javax.activation-1.2.0.jar&quot;);

Why didn’t it throw an exception?  Because java.net.URL is a very old class.  It was part of Java 1.0.  It didn’t do rigorous checking of syntax.

Why didn’t they fix it?  Because in object-oriented design, you *never* break existing code that utilizes public classes and public class members.  So, instead, Java added a new class, [java.net.URI](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/net/URI.html), which *does* do rigorous syntax checking.  This code would throw an exception, as it should:

    URI uri = new URI(&quot;file:&quot; + &quot;C:\\Users\\Test\\Downloads\\javax.activation-1.2.0.jar&quot;);

The proper way to convert a file name to a URL is:

    Path path = Path.of(&quot;C:\\Users\\Test\\Downloads\\javax.activation-1.2.0.jar&quot;);
    assert Files.isReadable(path) : &quot;File \&quot;&quot; + path + &quot;\&quot; does not exist!&quot;;

    URL activationJarURL = path.toUri().toURL();

The second problem is that Java doesn’t use a thread’s context classloader.  So, calling `Thread.currentThread().setContextClassLoader(classLoader);` essentially does nothing.  There do exist some libraries and some Java SE APIs that make use of the context classloader, but regular classloading won’t use it.

This actually does work:

    Class.forName(&quot;javax.activation.MimeTypeParseException&quot;, true, classLoader);

But the next line is not using the new ClassLoader at all:

    // Error --- not using classLoader, so cannot find javax.activation package
    TarArchive tar = new TarArchive(new FileOutputStream(archive));

What you need is a separate class which can be loaded by `classLoader`, which in turn calls `new TarArchive`.  If that class is in the same .jar or module as your application, it almost certainly will already be loaded by the current ClassLoader and therefore will not see the activation classes, so it will need to be in a separate .jar (not just a separate package).

    // This class must be in a separate .jar file.
    public class ArchiveWriter
    implements Runnable {
        private final File archive;

        public ArchiveWriter(File archive) {
            this.archive = Objects.requireNonNull(archive,
                &quot;Archive file cannot be null.&quot;);
        }

        @Override
        public void run() {
            try {
                TarArchive tar = new TarArchive(new FileOutputStream(archive));
                // etc.
            } catch (IOException e) {
                throw new UncheckedIOException(e);
            }
        }
    }

Now your `main` method can load that class using a custom ClassLoader which uses the [platform ClassLoader](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/ClassLoader.html#getPlatformClassLoader()) as a parent, and which refers to both the URL of the .jar containing the above class and the Java Activation Framework .jar.

    Path jafJarPath =
        Path.of(&quot;C:\\Users\\Test\\Downloads\\javax.activation-1.2.0.jar&quot;);

    Path tarProcessingJar =
        Path.of(&quot;C:\\Users\\Test\\archive-processor\\target\\archive-processor.jar&quot;);

    Collection&lt;URL&gt; urls = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    urls.add(jafJarPath.toUri().toURL());
    urls.add(tarProcessingJar.toUri().toURL());

    ClassLoader loader = new URLClassLoader(urls.toArray(URL[]::new),
        ClassLoader.getPlatformClassLoader());

Now we can use it to load the class:

    Class&lt;? extends Runnable&gt; archiveWriterClass =
        Class.forName(&quot;ArchiveWriter&quot;, true, loader).asSubclass(
            Runnable.class);

    Runnable archiveWriter =
        archiveWriterClass.getConstructor(File.class).newInstance(archive);

    archiveWriter.run();

If you need to pass more information and/or return information, you can use any interface other than Runnable.  You can even make up your own interface.  For example:

    public interface Archiver {
        int createArchive(Path archive,
                          Path... sourceDirs)
        throws IOException;
    }

And of course, ArchiveWriter can have any constructor(s) you wish, as long as you specify the constructor’s signature correctly when you call `getConstructor`.

